  "author_association": "NONE",
  "body": "Hi, I just started playing with kubernetes v1.1.1 on AWS using the following config:\n\n```\nexport KUBERNETES_PROVIDER=aws\nexport KUBE_AWS_ZONE=eu-west-1a\nexport NUM_MINIONS=1\nexport MASTER_SIZE=c4.large\nexport MINION_SIZE=r3.large\nexport AWS_S3_REGION=eu-west-1\nexport AWS_S3_BUCKET=xxx\nexport KUBE_AWS_INSTANCE_PREFIX=xxx\n```\n\nUnfortunately the very first thing I encountered was that cluster monitoring addon was broken. Apparently the heapster RC was missing. I found out that the [RC spec for heapster](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cluster/addons/cluster-monitoring/influxdb/heapster-controller.yaml#L2) relies on `num_nodes` salt variable, which gets defined by [cluster/aws/templates/create-dynamic-salt-files.sh](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cluster/aws/templates/create-dynamic-salt-files.sh#L43), which on the other hand is invoked by the [k8s master start (user data) script](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cluster/aws/util.sh#L876). Unfortunately the variable that `create-dynamic-salt-files.sh` relies on (NUM_MINIONS) is not provided to the master start script, hence `num_nodes` gets no value (in fact it evaluates to None, which can be observed later on in salt logs).\n\nI'll provide a patch for this issue but I haven't signed the CLA yet, so feel free to fix this on your own.\n\nBTW, does anyone test Kubernetes on AWS regularly or at least just before a release is made? Is AWS support considered official/stable? I mostly use default configs and this is not the first time I encounter such a fundamental issue.\n",
